Boil a full #kettle{}.

While it boils, chop the @potatoes{450%g} into 2cm chunks (no need to peel).

Pour the boiling water into a large #saucepan{} with @salt{1/2%tsp}.

Add the potatoes to the water and cook until you can easily slip a knife through, 
~{15-18%minutes}.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @oil{a drizzle} in a large #frying pan{} on 
medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the @British chicken breast{260%g}(diced) and 
@mushrooms{120%g}(sliced) to the frying pan. Season with @salt{} and 
@ground black pepper{}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its packaging.

Cook until browned all over, ~{5-6%minutes}. Stir occasionally.

Meanwhile, finely chop the @prunes{40%g} into 1cm pieces. Peel and grate the 
@garlic{2%cloves} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Add the garlic to the chicken and mushrooms for the final ~{1%minute} of cooking 
and stir-fry until fragrant.

Pour in the @water{275%ml} for the sauce and bring to a boil. Stir in the 
@red wine jus paste{22%g}, then reduce the heat to medium-high.

> TIP: If your red wine jus paste has hardened, pop it in a bowl of hot water for 1 min.

Stir the prunes, @mixed herbs{1%sachet} and @red wine stock paste{28%g} into the 
sauce.

Simmer, stirring regularly, until the sauce has thickened and the chicken is cooked 
through, ~{7-8%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Meanwhile, once the potatoes are cooked, drain in a #colander{} and return to the 
saucepan, off the heat. Add a knob of @butter{20%g} and a splash of @?milk{} and 
mash with a #potato masher{} until smooth.

Season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{}. Cover with a #lid{} to keep warm.

When the sauce has thickened, stir in the butter until melted.

Add a splash of @?water{} if it's a little too thick.

Share the mash between your #serving bowls{}.

Spoon over the red wine chicken and mushroom stew. Enjoy!